About
The Carnavalet Museum is dedicated to the history of Paris and its inhabitants and has collections illustrating the evolution of the city from prehistory through to the present day. A vast array of works of art, relics and models are displayed in 100 or so rooms, showing the capital at various periods in history and evoking intellectual and everyday life. Magnificent restored historical scenery creates an evocative setting for a stroll through the centuries in an enriching, delightful visitor experience.
Duration: More than 3 hours

Brad
Hong Kong, China177,757 contributions
Nicely organised History of Paris museum
Aug 2024 Couples
This is a very good museum situated within the historic Hotel le Peleteier de Saint Fargeau and the Hotel Carnavalet along Rue de Svigne in the Marais district. Opening hours are 10am to 6pm daily (closed on Mondays) and entry is free to the public.

The museum serves as a brief history of Paris stretching back to Neolithic times to the present. There are galleries with antiquity, artefacts, artworks, sculptures, furniture and representation of important time periods including Gallo-Roman Paris, Medieval, the Renaissance, Louis XV, Revolutionary times and even the turn of the century when Art Nouveau was having its day.

There is a route that allows you to make a chronological visit through the eras. At a leisurely pace, best to allow at least 90 minutes. If you are enjoying what you see, a 3+ hour visit might be more appropriate. Like most Paris museums, you'll find lockers, easy to locate toilets, gift shop and a cafe/restaurant at Carnavalet if needed.
Written October 21, 2024

Sep 2024 Solo
On a recent trip to Paris, I had the opportunity to spend an hour and a half in the fabulous Musee Carnavalet Historic de Paris.

Opened in 1880, (mind boggling that the city fathers recognized the need so early on), the museum is part art museum, history lesson, and historic home tour.

I loved it!

In my short time there, I didnt even scratch the surface, of all that delightful museum contains. Its wonderfully well done, easy to follow, and unbelievably its FREE
